        "content": "<p>Hi! I'm trying to state/prove a theorem with a hypothesis that looks something like \"Suppose X follows the uniform distribution over some set S.\" That is, </p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>∼</mo><mi>U</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>i</mi><mi>f</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\sim Uniform(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∼</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ni</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">or</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>I'm getting caught up on how to express this hypothesis, specifically the idea that some object \"follows\" a distribution in Lean. Currently I'm trying to use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Probability/Distributions/Uniform.html#PMF.uniformOfFinset\">PMF.uniformOfFinset</a> to represent my distribution, but I'm not sure this is the correct approach. Thanks for the help :)</p>",
        "id": 480396764,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Whitty",
        "timestamp": 1730711380
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You could use <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Probability/UniformOn.html#ProbabilityTheory.uniformOn\">ProbabilityTheory.uniformOn</a> for the uniform measure over a finite set.<br>\nThe way to write that <code>X</code> has that distribution in a measurable space with probability measure <code>P</code> is <code>P.map X = uniformOn S</code>.</p>\n<p>Take a look at the blog post <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/blog/posts/basic-probability-in-mathlib/\">https://leanprover-community.github.io/blog/posts/basic-probability-in-mathlib/</a> for other common questions of the type \"how do I express the probability related thing X in Mathlib?\".</p>",
        "id": 480398177,
        "sender_full_name": "Rémy Degenne",
        "timestamp": 1730711946
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Note that for continuous uniform distributions we have <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Probability/Distributions/Uniform.html#MeasureTheory.pdf.IsUniform\">IsUniform</a></p>",
        "id": 480410318,
        "sender_full_name": "Kexing Ying",
        "timestamp": 1730715306
    },
